# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: british-deaf-association
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] As a hearing child of Deaf parents (CODA), his first language was British Sign Language.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] After attending Moseley Grammar school, Verney trained as a Deaf Welfare officer.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] He then studied Social Work at Liverpool Polytechnic (1964–66).
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] In 1970, Verney took up a position as the first director of the course in social work with deaf people at the North London Polytechnic and in 1975 he became social work services officer at the Welsh Office.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] In 1980, Verney became general secretary of the British Deaf Association (BDA).
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] At the time, it was a charity mostly run by hearing people.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] Verney was responsible for transforming it into an organisation led by Deaf people and for the campaigning arm of the association.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] In 1983, Jock Young, the first Deaf chairman of the association, was elected.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] Verney helped to establish a training course at Durham University for Deaf people to become sign language teachers, and in 1982 he established what would become the Sign Language week, aimed at promoting the awareness and use of British Sign Language.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] In 1989 the BDA had more than one million pound in income for the first time and that was much due to his work.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] Verney was one of the promoters, together with Jock Young, of the European Union of the Deaf, which was launched in 1985 as the European Community Regional Secretariat, bringing together Deaf associations from Germany, the Netherlands and France to work together to empower Deaf people across Europe.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] Verney became the EUD's executive officer from 1989 to 1992.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] He also helped founding the European Disability Forum (EDF).
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] In 1992, following a successful funding application, Verney became European regional officer of Disabled People's International, working alongside disability rights campaigner Rachel Hurst.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] Among his achievements, he organised a Disabled People's parliament (December 1993), where 440 disabled people took the place of the MEPs and reported to the European Commission in first person, and he ran workshops across Europe on human rights, bioethics, independent living and accessibility.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] He took also part in the Campaign for Independent Living.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] He was forced to stand down in 2002 due to ill health.
[src:british-deaf-association/arthur-verney] He married Ann Hilder in 1968, and together had a daughter.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The **British Broadcasting Corporation** (**BBC**) is a British public service broadcaster that serves as the primary national public broadcasting company of the United Kingdom, headquartered at Broadcasting House in London, England.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Originally established in 1922 as the British Broadcasting Company, it evolved into its current state with its current name on 1 January 1927.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] It is the oldest and largest local and global broadcaster by stature and by number of employees, with a total staff of 21,000.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC was established under a royal charter, and operates under an agreement with the secretary of state for culture, media and sport.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Its work is funded principally by an annual television licence fee which is charged to all British households, companies, and organisations using any type of equipment to receive or record live television broadcasts or to use the BBC's streaming service, iPlayer.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The fee is set by the British government, agreed by Parliament, and is used to fund the BBC's radio, TV, and online services covering the nations and regions of the UK.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Since 1 April 2014, it has also funded the BBC World Service (launched in 1932 as the BBC Empire Service), which broadcasts in 43 languages as of 2026.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Some of the BBC's revenue comes from its commercial subsidiary BBC Studios (formerly BBC Worldwide), which sells BBC programs and services internationally and also distributes the BBC's international 24-hour English-language news services BBC News, and from BBC.com, provided by BBC Global News Ltd.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Since its formation on 18 October 1922, the BBC has played a prominent role in British life and culture.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] It is sometimes informally referred to as **the Beeb** or **Auntie**.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1923 it launched *Radio Times* (subtitled "The official organ of the BBC"), the first broadcast listings magazine; the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11 million copies, the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Britain's first live public broadcast was made from the factory of Marconi Company in Chelmsford in June 1920.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] It was sponsored by the *Daily Mail*'s Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe and featured the famous Australian soprano Dame Nellie Melba.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The Melba broadcast caught the people's imagination and marked a turning point in the British public's attitude to radio.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] However, this public enthusiasm was not shared in official circles where such broadcasts were held to interfere with important military and civil communications.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] By late 1920, the pressure from these quarters and uneasiness among the staff of the licensing authority, the General Post Office (GPO), was sufficient to lead to a ban on further Chelmsford broadcasts.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] But by 1922 the GPO had received nearly 100 broadcast licence requests and moved to rescind its ban in the wake of a petition by 63 wireless societies with over 3,000 members.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] John Reith, a Scottish Calvinist, was appointed its general manager in December 1922 a few weeks after the company made its first official broadcast.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Stanton Jefferies was its first director of music.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The company was to be financed by a royalty on the sale of BBC wireless receiving sets from approved domestic manufacturers.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] To this day, the BBC aims to follow the Reithian directive to "inform, educate and entertain".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The financial arrangements soon proved inadequate.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Set sales were disappointing as amateurs made their own receivers and listeners bought rival unlicensed sets.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] By mid-1923, discussions between the GPO and the BBC had become deadlocked and the Postmaster General commissioned a review of broadcasting by the Sykes Committee.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The committee recommended a short-term reorganisation of licence fees with improved enforcement to address the BBC's immediate financial distress, and an increased share of the licence revenue split between it and the GPO.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] This was to be followed by a simple 10 shillings licence fee to fund broadcasts.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC's broadcasting monopoly was made explicit for the duration of its current broadcast licence, as was the prohibition on advertising.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] To avoid competition with newspapers, Fleet Street persuaded the government to ban news bulletins before 7 pm and the BBC was required to source all news from external wire services.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The *Radio Times*, the world's first and longest-running radio and television listings magazine, was launched by Reith in September 1923.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The first edition, subtitled "The official organ of the BBC", was priced at tuppence (two pence) on newsstands, and quickly sold out its run of a quarter of a million copies.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Mid-1925 found the future of broadcasting under further consideration, this time by the Crawford committee.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] By now the BBC, under Reith's leadership, had forged a consensus favouring a continuation of the unified (monopoly) broadcasting service, but more money was still required to finance rapid expansion.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Wireless manufacturers were anxious to exit the loss-making consortium, and Reith was keen that the BBC be seen as a public service rather than a commercial enterprise.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The recommendations of the Crawford Committee were published in March the following year and were still under consideration by the GPO when the 1926 United Kingdom general strike broke out in May.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The strike temporarily interrupted newspaper production, and with restrictions on news bulletins waived, the BBC suddenly became the primary source of news for the duration of the crisis.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The crisis placed the BBC in a delicate position.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On the one hand Reith was acutely aware that the government might exercise its right to commandeer the BBC at any time as a mouthpiece of the government if the BBC were to step out of line, but on the other he was anxious to maintain public trust by appearing to be acting independently.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The government was divided on how to handle the BBC, but ended up trusting Reith, whose opposition to the strike mirrored the PM's own.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Although Winston Churchill in particular wanted to commandeer the BBC to use it "to the best possible advantage", Reith wrote that Stanley Baldwin's government wanted to be able to say "that they did not commandeer [the BBC], but they know that they can trust us not to be really impartial".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Thus the BBC was granted sufficient leeway to pursue the government's objectives largely in a manner of its own choosing.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Supporters of the strike nicknamed the BBC the BFC for British Falsehood Company.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Reith personally announced the end of the strike which he marked by reciting from Blake's "Jerusalem" signifying that England had been saved.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] While the BBC tends to characterise its coverage of the general strike by emphasising the positive impression created by its balanced coverage of the views of government and strikers, Seaton has characterised the episode as the invention of "modern propaganda in its British form".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Reith argued that trust gained by 'authentic impartial news' could then be used.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Impartial news was not necessarily an end in itself.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The British Broadcasting Corporation came into existence on 1 January 1927, and Reith – newly knighted – was appointed its first director general.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] To represent its purpose and (stated) values, the new corporation adopted the coat of arms, including the motto "Nation shall speak peace unto Nation".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] British radio audiences had little choice apart from BBC's programming approach.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Reith was viewed as taking a moralistic approach as an executive, aiming to broadcast "all that is best in every department of human knowledge, endeavour and achievement", and putting the programming in moral or ethical terms, advocating "a high moral tone" as "obviously of paramount importance".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Reith succeeded in building a high wall against a more tabloid, free-for-all in radio aimed at merely attracting the largest audience (and advertising revenue).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] There was no paid advertising on the BBC; all the revenue came from a tax on receiving sets.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Highbrow audiences, however, greatly enjoyed it.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] At a time when American, Australian and Canadian stations were drawing huge audiences cheering for their local teams with the broadcast of baseball, rugby and hockey, the BBC emphasised service for a national rather than a regional audience.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Boat races were well covered along with tennis and horse racing, but the BBC was reluctant to spend its severely limited air time on long football or cricket games, regardless of their popularity.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] John Reith and the BBC, with support from the Crown, determined the universal needs of the people of Britain and broadcast content according to these perceived standards.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Reith effectively censored anything that he felt would be harmful, directly or indirectly.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] While recounting his time with the BBC in 1935, Raymond Postgate claims that BBC broadcasters were made to submit a draft of their potential broadcast for approval.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] It was expected that they tailored their content to accommodate the modest, church-going elderly or a member of the Clergy.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Until 1928, entertainers broadcasting on the BBC, both singers and "talkers" were expected to avoid biblical quotations, Clerical impersonations and references, references to drink or Prohibition in the United States, vulgar and doubtful matter and political allusions.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC excluded popular foreign music and musicians from its broadcasts, while promoting British alternatives.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 5 March 1928, Stanley Baldwin, the Prime Minister, maintained the censorship of editorial opinions on public policy, but allowed the BBC to address matters of religious, political or industrial controversy.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The resulting political "talk series", designed to inform England on political issues, were criticised by members of parliament, including Winston Churchill, David Lloyd George and Sir Austen Chamberlain.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Those who opposed these chats claimed that they silence the opinions of those in Parliament who are not nominated by Party Leaders or Party Whips, thus stifling independent, non-official views.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In October 1932, the policemen of the Metropolitan Police Federation marched in protest at a proposed pay cut.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Fearing dissent within the police force and public support for the movement, the BBC censored its coverage of the events, only broadcasting official statements from the government.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Throughout the 1930s political broadcasts had been monitored by the BBC.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1935, the BBC censored the broadcasts of Oswald Mosley and Harry Pollitt.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Mosley was a leader of the British Union of Fascists, and Pollitt a leader of the Communist Party of Great Britain.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] They were contracted to provide a series of five broadcasts on their parties' politics.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC, in conjunction with The Foreign Office of Britain, suspended this series and ultimately cancelled it without the notice of the public.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1938, Winston Churchill proposed a series of talks regarding British domestic and foreign politics and affairs but was censored.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The censorship of political discourse by the BBC started the shutdown of the political debate that manifested over the BBC's wartime airwaves.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The Foreign Office maintained that the public should not be aware of their role in the censorship.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] From 1935 to 1939, the BBC attempted to unite the British Empire's radio waves, sending staff to Egypt, Palestine, Newfoundland, Jamaica, India, Canada and South Africa.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Reith visited South Africa, lobbying for state-run radio programmes accepted by South African Parliament in 1936.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] A similar programme was adopted in Canada.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Through collaboration with these state-run broadcasting centres, Reith had an influence on the culture across the empire of Great Britain with his departure from the corporation in 1938.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Experimental television broadcasts were started in 1929 using an electromechanical 30-line system developed by John Logie Baird.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The superiority of the electronic system saw the mechanical system dropped early the following year, with the Marconi-EMI system the first fully electronic television system in the world to be used in regular broadcasting.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The success of broadcasting provoked animosities between the BBC and well-established media such as theatres, concert halls and the recording industry.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] By 1929, the BBC complained that the agents of many comedians refused to sign contracts for broadcasting, because they feared it harmed the artist "by making his material stale" and that it "reduces the value of the artist as a visible music-hall performer".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Television broadcasting was suspended from 1 September 1939 to 7 June 1946, during World War II, and it was left to BBC Radio broadcasters such as Reginald Foort to keep the nation's spirits up.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC moved most of its radio operations out of London, initially to Bristol, and then to Bedford.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] BBC employees during the war included George Orwell who spent two years with the broadcaster.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] During his role as prime minister during the war, Winston Churchill delivered 33 major wartime speeches by radio, all of which were carried by the BBC within the UK.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 18 June 1940, French general Charles de Gaulle, in exile in London as the leader of the Free French, made a speech, broadcast by the BBC, urging the French people not to capitulate to the Nazis.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In October 1940, Princesses Elizabeth and Margaret made their first radio broadcast for the BBC's *Children's Hour*, addressing other children who had been evacuated from cities.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1938 John Reith and the Government of the United Kingdom, specifically the Ministry of Information which had been set up for WWII, designed a censorship apparatus for the inevitability of war.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Due to the BBC's advancements in shortwave radio technology, the corporation could broadcast across the world during the Second World War.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Within Europe, the BBC European Service would gather intelligence and information regarding the current events of the war in English.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Regional BBC workers, based on their regional geo-political climate, would then further censor the material their broadcasts would cover.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Nothing was to be added outside the preordained news items.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] For example, the BBC Polish Service was heavily censored due to fears of jeopardising relations with the Soviet Union.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Controversial topics, i.e. the contested Polish and Soviet border, the deportation of Polish citizens, the arrests of Polish Home Army members and the Katyn massacre, were not included in Polish broadcasts.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] American radio broadcasts were broadcast across Europe on BBC channels.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] This material also passed through the BBC's censorship office, which surveilled and edited American coverage of British affairs.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] By 1940, across all BBC broadcasts, music by composers from enemy nations was censored.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In total, 99 German, 38 Austrian and 38 Italian composers were censored.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC argued that like the Italian or German languages, listeners would be irritated by the inclusion of enemy composers.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Any potential broadcasters said to have pacifist, communist or fascist ideologies were not allowed on the BBC's airwaves.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1937, a MI5 security officer was given a permanent office within the organisation.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] This officer would examine the files of potential political subversives and mark the files of those deemed a security risk to the organisation, blacklisting them.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] This was often done on spurious grounds; even so, the practice would continue and expand during the years of the Cold War.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] There was a widely reported urban myth that, upon resumption of the BBC television service after the war, announcer Leslie Mitchell started by saying, "As I was saying before we were so rudely interrupted ...".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In fact, the first person to appear when transmission resumed was Jasmine Bligh and the words said were, "Good afternoon, everybody.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Do you remember me, Jasmine Bligh...?" The European Broadcasting Union was formed on 12 February 1950, in Torquay with the BBC among the 23 founding broadcasting organizations.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Competition to the BBC was introduced in 1955, with the commercial and independently operated television network of Independent Television (ITV).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] However, the BBC monopoly on radio services would persist until 8 October 1973 when under the control of the newly renamed Independent Broadcasting Authority (IBA), the UK's first Independent local radio station, LBC came on-air in the London area.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] BBC2 used the higher resolution 625-line standard which had been standardised across Europe.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] BBC2 was broadcast in colour from 1 July 1967 and was joined by BBC1 and ITV on 15 November 1969.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The 405-line VHF transmissions of BBC1 (and ITV) were continued for compatibility with older television receivers until 1985.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Starting in 1964, a series of pirate radio stations (starting with Radio Caroline) came on the air and forced the British government finally to regulate radio services to permit nationally based advertising-financed services.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In response, the BBC reorganised and renamed their radio channels.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 30 September 1967, the Light Programme was split into Radio 1 offering continuous "Popular" music and Radio 2 more "Easy Listening".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The "Third" programme became Radio 3 offering classical music and cultural programming.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The Home Service became Radio 4 offering news, and non-musical content such as quiz shows, readings, dramas and plays.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] As well as the four national channels, a series of local BBC radio stations were established in 1967, including Radio London.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1969, the BBC Enterprises department was formed to exploit BBC brands and programmes for commercial spin-off products.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1979, it became a wholly owned limited company, BBC Enterprises Ltd.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1974 the BBC's teletext service, Ceefax, was introduced, created initially to provide subtitling, but developed into a news and information service.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1978, BBC staff went on strike just before the Christmas, thus blocking out the transmission of both channels and amalgamating all four radio stations into one.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Since the deregulation of the UK television and radio market in the 1980s, the BBC has faced increased competition from the commercial sector (and from the advertiser-funded public service broadcaster Channel 4), especially on satellite television, cable television, and digital television services.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In the late 1980s, the BBC began a process of divestment by spinning off and selling parts of its organisation.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1988, it sold off the Hulton Press Library, a photographic archive which had been acquired from the *Picture Post* magazine by the BBC in 1957.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The archive was sold to Brian Deutsch and is now owned by Getty Images.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1987, the BBC decided to centralise its operations by the management team with the radio and television divisions joining forces together for the first time, the activities of the news and currents departments and coordinated jointly under the new directorate.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] During the 1990s, this process continued with the separation of certain operational arms of the corporation into autonomous but wholly owned subsidiaries, with the aim of generating additional revenue for programme-making.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] BBC Enterprises was reorganised and relaunched in 1995, as BBC Worldwide Ltd.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1998, BBC studios, outside broadcasts, post production, design, costumes and wigs were spun off into BBC Resources Ltd.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC Research & Development has played a major part in the development of broadcasting and recording techniques.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC was also responsible for the development of the NICAM stereo standard.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The new station would be a news and sport station.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1997, BBC News 24, a rolling news channel, launched on digital television services, and the following year, BBC Choice was launched as the third general entertainment channel from the BBC.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC also purchased The Parliamentary Channel, which was renamed BBC Parliament.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1999, BBC Knowledge launched as a multimedia channel, with services available on the newly launched BBC Text digital teletext service (later rebranded as BBC Red Button), and on BBC Online.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The channel had an educational aim, which was modified later on in its life to offer documentaries.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 2002 several television and radio channels were reorganised.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] BBC Knowledge was replaced by BBC Four and became the BBC's arts and documentaries channel.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] CBBC, which had been a programming strand as Children's BBC since 1985, was split into CBBC and CBeebies, for younger children, with both new services getting a digital channel: the CBBC Channel and CBeebies Channel.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In addition to the television channels, new digital radio stations were created: 1Xtra, 6 Music and Radio 4 Extra.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] BBC 1Xtra was a sister station to Radio 1 and specialised in modern black music, BBC 6 Music specialised in alternative music genres and BBC7 specialised in archive, speech and children's programming.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 2008, another channel was launched, BBC Alba, a Scottish Gaelic service.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 2006 BBC HD was launched as an experimental service, becoming official in December 2007.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The channel broadcast HD simulcasts of programmes on BBC One, BBC Two, BBC Three and BBC Four as well as repeats of some older programmes in HD.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 2010, an HD simulcast of BBC One launched: BBC One HD.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The channel uses HD versions of BBC One's schedule and uses upscaled versions of programmes not currently produced in HD.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC HD channel closed in March 2013 and was replaced by BBC Two HD in the same month.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The 2004 Hutton Inquiry and the subsequent report raised questions about the BBC's journalistic standards and its impartiality.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] This led to resignations of senior management members at the time including the then Director General, Greg Dyke.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In January 2007, the BBC released minutes of the board meeting which led to Greg Dyke's resignation.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC's IT, telephony and broadcast technology were brought together as BBC Technology Ltd in 2001, and the division was later sold to the German company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] SIS was subsequently acquired from Siemens by the French company Atos.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Further divestments included BBC Books (sold to Random House in 2006); BBC Outside Broadcasts Ltd (sold in 2008 to Satellite Information Services); Costumes and Wigs (stock sold in 2008 to Angels Costumes); and BBC Magazines (sold to Immediate Media Company in 2011).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] After the sales of OBs and costumes, the remainder of BBC Resources was reorganised as BBC Studios and Post Production, which continues today as a wholly owned subsidiary of the BBC.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 7 March 2005 director general Mark Thompson launched the "Creative Futures" project to restructure the organisation.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] A strike in May 2005 by more than 11,000 BBC workers over a proposal to cut 4,000 jobs and to privatise parts of the BBC, disrupted much of the BBC's regular programming.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The blueprint for the future of the BBC resulting from the project was published ion 25 April 2006.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 18 October 2007, Thompson announced a six-year plan, "Delivering Creative Futures", which included merging the television current affairs department into a new "News Programmes" division.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Thompson's announcement, in response to a £2 billion shortfall in funding, would, he said, deliver "a smaller but fitter BBC" in the digital age, by cutting its payroll and, in 2013, selling Television Centre.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The plans included a reduction in posts of 2,500; including 1,800 redundancies, consolidating news operations, reducing programming output by 10% and selling off the flagship Television Centre building in London.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 20 October 2010 the Chancellor of the Exchequer George Osborne announced that the television licence fee would be frozen at its current level until the end of the current charter in 2016.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The same announcement revealed that the BBC would take on the full cost of running the BBC World Service and the BBC Monitoring service from the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office, and partially finance the Welsh broadcaster S4C.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] BBC HD was closed on 26 March 2013, and replaced with an HD simulcast of BBC Two; however, flagship programmes, other channels and full funding for CBBC and CBeebies would be retained.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Numerous BBC facilities have been sold off, including New Broadcasting House on Wilmslow Road in Manchester.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Many major departments have been relocated to Broadcasting House in central London and MediaCityUK in Salford, particularly since the closure of BBC Television Centre in March 2013.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 16 February 2016, the BBC Three television service was discontinued and replaced by a digital outlet under the same name, targeting its young adult audience with web series and other content.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Under the new royal charter instituted in 2017, the corporation must publish an annual report to Ofcom, outlining its plans and public service obligations for the next year.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In its 2017–18 report, released July 2017, the BBC announced plans to "re-invent" its output to better compete against commercial streaming services such as Netflix.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Since 2017, the BBC has also funded the Local Democracy Reporting Service, with up to 165 journalists employed by independent news organisations to report on local democracy issues on a pooled basis.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 2016 the BBC Director General Tony Hall announced a savings target of £800 million per year by 2021, which is about 23% of annual licence fee revenue.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Having to take on the £700 million cost for free TV licences for the over-75 pensioners, and rapid inflation in drama and sport coverage costs, was given as the reason.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Duplication of management and content spending would be reduced, and there would be a review of BBC News.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In September 2019 the BBC launched the Trusted News Initiative to work with news and social media companies to combat disinformation about national elections.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 2020 the BBC announced a BBC News savings target of £80 million per year by 2022, involving about 520 staff reductions.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC's director of news and current affairs Fran Unsworth said there would be further moves toward digital broadcasting, in part to attract back a youth audience, and more pooling of reporters to stop separate teams covering the same news.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 2020, the BBC reported a £119 million deficit because of delays to cost reduction plans, and the forthcoming ending of the remaining £253 million funding towards pensioner licence fees would increase financial pressures.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In March 2023 the BBC was at the centre of a political row with football pundit Gary Lineker, after he criticised the British government's asylum policy on social media.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Lineker was suspended from his position on *Match of the Day* before being re-instated after receiving overwhelming support from his colleagues.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The scandal was made worse due to the connections between BBC's chairman, Richard Sharp, and the Conservative Party.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In April 2023 Richard Sharp resigned as chairman after a report found he did not disclose potential perceived conflicts of interest in his role in the facilitation of a loan to Prime Minister Boris Johnson.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Dame Elan Closs Stephens was appointed as acting chairwoman on 27 June 2023, and she would lead the BBC board for a year or until a new permanent chair has been appointed.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Samir Shah was subsequently appointed with effect from 4 March 2024.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In October 2024 it was announced that the BBC along with Sky Sports signed a deal to broadcast the 2025–26 season of the Women's Super League campaign.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In May 2025, BBC director general Tim Davie said there were plans to switch off traditional broadcast transmissions in the 2030s to transition to a fully online delivery of programmes.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In November 2025, following the leaking of a report that alleged systemic bias within the BBC, Tim Davie resigned as Director-General along with Deborah Turness as CEO of News within the organisation.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 16 December 2025, the UK government considered a green paper of new ways to fund the BBC, such as replacing the television licence with either advertising or a subscription model.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 25 March 2026, former Google executive Matt Brittin was appointed as the new Director-General.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] On 15 April 2026, BBC announced cuts up to 2,000 jobs—its largest layoffs in over a decade—to reduce costs by about 10% (around £500 million) over the next two years.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC is a chartered corporation, independent from direct government intervention, with its activities being overseen from April 2017 by the BBC Board and regulated by Ofcom.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC is a public broadcasting company that operates under a royal charter.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The charter is the constitutional basis for the BBC, and sets out the BBC's object, mission and public purposes.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] It emphasises public service, (limited) editorial independence, prohibits advertising on domestic services and proclaims the BBC is to "seek to avoid adverse impacts on competition which are not necessary for the effective fulfilment of the Mission and the promotion of the Public Purposes".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The charter additionally sets out that the BBC is subject to an additional agreement between it and the Culture Secretary, and that its operating licence is to be set by Ofcom, an external regulatory body.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] It used to be that the Home Secretary be departmental to both the agreement as well as the licence, and regulatory duties fall to the BBC Trust, but the 2017 charter changed those 2007 arrangements.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The charter also outlines the BBC's governance and regulatory arrangements as a statutory corporation, including the role and composition of the BBC Board.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The current charter took effect on 1 January 2017 and is set to expire on 31 December 2027; the agreement being coterminous.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] It replaced the previous governing body, the BBC Trust, which itself had replaced the board of governors in 2007.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The board sets the strategy for the corporation, assesses the performance of the BBC's executive board in delivering the BBC's services, and appoints the director-general.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Ofcom is responsible for the regulation of the BBC.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Samir Shah has served as the chairman since 4 March 2024.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The executive committee is responsible for the day-to-day operations of the broadcaster.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Consisting of senior managers of the BBC, the committee meets once per month and is responsible for operational management and delivery of services within a framework set by the board, and is chaired by the director-general, who is chief executive and (from 1994) editor-in-chief.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] From as early as the 1930s until the 1990s, MI5, the British domestic intelligence service, engaged in the vetting of applicants for BBC jobs, a policy designed to keep out persons deemed subversive.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1933, BBC executive Colonel Alan Dawnay began to meet the head of MI5, Sir Vernon Kell, to informally trade information; from 1935, a formal arrangement was made whereby job applicants would be secretly vetted by MI5 for their political views (without their knowledge).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] The BBC took up a policy of denying any suggestion by the press of such a relationship (the very existence of MI5 itself was not officially acknowledged until the Security Service Act 1989).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] This relationship garnered wider public attention after an article by David Leigh and Paul Lashmar appeared in *The Observer* in August 1985, revealing that MI5 had been vetting appointments, running operations from Room 105 in Broadcasting House.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] At the time of the exposé, the operation was being run by Ronnie Stonham.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] A memo from 1984 revealed that blacklisted organisations included the far-left Communist Party of Great Britain, the Socialist Workers Party, the Workers Revolutionary Party and the Militant tendency, as well as the far-right National Front and the British National Party.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] An association with one of these groups could result in a denial of a job application.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In October 1985 the BBC announced that it would stop the vetting process, except for a few people in top roles, as well as those in charge of Wartime Broadcasting Service emergency broadcasting (in the event of a nuclear war) and staff of the BBC World Service.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] In 1990, following the Security Service Act 1989, vetting was further restricted to those responsible for wartime broadcasting and those with access to secret government information.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p01] Michael Hodder, who succeeded Stonham, had the MI5 vetting files sent to the BBC Archives in Reading, Berkshire.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC has the second largest budget of any UK-based broadcaster with an operating expenditure of £4.722 billion in 2013/14 compared with £6.471 billion for Sky UK in 2013/14 and £1.843 billion for ITV in the calendar year 2013.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The principal means of funding the BBC is through the television licence, costing £169.50 per year per household as of April 2024.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Such a licence is required to legally receive broadcast television across the UK, the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] No licence is required to own a television used for other means, or for sound only radio sets (though a separate licence for these was also required for non-TV households until 1971).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The cost of a television licence is set by the government and enforced by the criminal law.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] A 50% discount is offered to people who are registered blind or severely visually impaired, and the licence is completely free for any household containing anyone aged 75 or over and receiving pension credit.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC pursues its licence fee collection and enforcement under the trading name "TV Licensing".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The revenue is collected privately by Capita, an outside agency, and is paid into the central government Consolidated Fund, a process defined in the Communications Act 2003.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Funds are then allocated by the Department for Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) and the Treasury and approved by Parliament via legislation.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Additional revenues are paid by the Department for Work and Pensions to compensate for subsidised licences for eligible over-75-year-olds.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The licence fee is classified as a tax, and its evasion is a criminal offence.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Since 1991, collection and enforcement of the licence fee has been the responsibility of the BBC in its role as TV Licensing Authority.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC carries out surveillance (mostly using subcontractors) on properties (under the auspices of the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000) and may conduct searches of a property using a search warrant.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] According to TV Licensing, 216,900 people in the UK were caught watching TV without a licence in 2018/19.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Licence fee evasion makes up about one-tenth of all cases prosecuted in magistrates' courts, representing 0.3% of court time.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Income from commercial enterprises and from overseas sales of its catalogue of programmes has substantially increased over recent years, with BBC Worldwide contributing some £243 million to the BBC's core public service business.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] But the licence fee has attracted criticism.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It has been argued that in an age of multi-stream, multi-channel availability, an obligation to pay a licence fee is no longer appropriate.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC's use of private sector company Capita to send letters to premises not paying the licence fee has been criticised, especially as there have been cases where such letters have been sent to premises which are up to date with their payments, or do not require a TV licence.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC uses advertising campaigns to inform customers of the requirement to pay the licence fee.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Past campaigns have been criticised by Conservative MP Boris Johnson and former MP Ann Widdecombe for having a threatening nature and language used to scare evaders into paying.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Audio clips and television broadcasts are used to inform listeners of the BBC's comprehensive database.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] There are a number of pressure groups campaigning on the issue of the licence fee.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In 2023, about half a million UK households cancelled their TV licence, driven by shifting viewing habits and financial pressures.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] As a result, the BBC saw a decline in revenue, with the number of households paying the licence fee dropping to 23.9 million.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The majority of the BBC's commercial output comes from its commercial arm BBC Worldwide which sell programmes abroad and exploit key brands for merchandise.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In April 2026, the BBC announced that they would be cutting between 1,800 and 2,000 jobs, citing a need to save £500 million over the coming two years.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House in Portland Place, central London, is the official headquarters of the BBC.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It is also the home of BBC News, which relocated to the building from BBC Television Centre in 2013.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] On the front of the building are statues of Prospero and Ariel, characters from William Shakespeare's play *The Tempest*, sculpted by Eric Gill.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Renovation of Broadcasting House began in 2002, and was completed in 2012.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Until it closed at the end of March 2013, BBC Television was based at Television Centre, a purpose-built television facility opened in 1960 located in White City, four miles (6 km) west of central London.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] This facility was host to a number of famous guests and programmes through the years, and its name and image is familiar with many British citizens.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Nearby, the White City Place complex contains numerous programme offices, housed in Centre House, the Media Centre and Broadcast Centre.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It is in this area around Shepherd's Bush that the majority of BBC employees worked.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] As part of a major reorganisation of BBC property, the entire BBC News operation relocated from the News Centre at BBC Television Centre to the refurbished Broadcasting House to create what is being described as "one of the world's largest live broadcast centres".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC News Channel and BBC News International relocated to the premises in early 2013.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House is now also home to most of the BBC's national radio stations, and the BBC World Service.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The major part of this plan involved the demolition of the two post-war extensions to the building and construction of an extension designed by Sir Richard MacCormac of MJP Architects.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] This move concentrated the BBC's London operations, allowing them to sell Television Centre.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] As well as the two main sites in London (Broadcasting House and White City), there are seven other important BBC production centres in the UK, mainly specialising in different productions.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Cardiff is home to BBC Cymru Wales, which specialises in drama production.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Open since 2012, and containing 7 new studios, Roath Lock is notable as the home of productions such as *Doctor Who* and *Casualty*.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Broadcasting House Belfast, home to BBC Northern Ireland, specialises in original drama and comedy, and has taken part in many co-productions with independent companies and notably with RTÉ in the Republic of Ireland.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Scotland, based in Pacific Quay, Glasgow is a large producer of programmes for the network, including several quiz shows.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In England, the larger regions also produce some programming.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Previously the largest hub of BBC programming from the regions had been BBC North West.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] At present they produce all religious and ethical programmes on the BBC, as well as other programmes such as *A Question of Sport*.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] However, this is to be merged and expanded under the BBC North project, which involved the region moving from New Broadcasting House, Manchester, to MediaCityUK.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Midlands, based at Mailbox Birmingham, also produces drama and contains the headquarters for the English regions and the BBC's daytime output.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Other production centres include Broadcasting House Bristol, home of BBC West and famously the BBC Studios Natural History Unit and to a lesser extent, Quarry Hill in Leeds, home of BBC Yorkshire.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] There are also many smaller local and regional studios throughout the UK, operating the BBC regional television services and the BBC Local Radio stations.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates several news gathering centres in various locations around the world, which provide news coverage of that region to the national and international news operations.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In 2004 the BBC contracted out its former BBC Technology division to the German engineering and electronics company Siemens IT Solutions and Services (SIS), outsourcing its IT, telephony and broadcast technology systems.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] When Atos Origin acquired the SIS division from Siemens in December 2010 for €850 million (£720m), the BBC support contract also passed to Atos, and in July 2011, the BBC announced to staff that its technology support would become an Atos service.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Siemens staff working on the BBC contract were transferred to Atos; the BBC's Information Technology systems are now managed by Atos.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In 2012, the BBC's then-chief technology officer John Linwood, expressed confidence in service improvements to the BBC's technology provision brought about by Atos.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] He also stated that supplier accountability had been strengthened following some high-profile technology failures which had taken place during the partnership with Siemens.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC operates several television channels nationally and internationally.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC One and BBC Two are the flagship television channels.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Others include the youth channel BBC Three, cultural and documentary channel BBC Four, the British and international variations of the BBC News channel, parliamentary channel BBC Parliament, and two children's channels, CBBC and CBeebies.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Digital television is now entrenched in the UK, with analogue transmission completely phased out as of December 2012.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC One is a regionalised TV service which provides opt-outs throughout the day for local news and other local programming.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] These variations are more pronounced in the BBC "Nations", i.e.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales, where the presentation is mostly carried out locally on BBC One and Two, and where programme schedules can vary considerably from that of the network.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Two variations exist in the Nations; however, English regions today rarely have the option to opt out as regional programming now exists only on BBC One.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In 2019, the Scottish variation of BBC Two ceased operation and was replaced with the networked version in favour of a new BBC Scotland channel.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Two was the first channel to be transmitted on 625 lines, in 1964.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It then carried a small-scale regular colour service from 1967.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] A new Scottish Gaelic television channel, BBC Alba, was launched in September 2008.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It is also the first multi-genre channel to come entirely from Scotland with almost all of its programmes made in Scotland.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The service was initially available only via satellite but since June 2011 has been available to viewers in Scotland on Freeview and cable television.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC currently operates HD simulcasts of all its nationwide channels with the exception of BBC Parliament.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Until 26 March 2013, a separate channel called BBC HD was available, in place of BBC Two HD.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It launched on 15 May 2006, following a 12-month trial of the broadcasts.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It became a proper channel in 2007, and screened HD programmes as simulcasts of the main network, or as repeats.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The corporation has been producing programmes in the format for many years, and stated that it hoped to produce 100% of new programmes in HDTV by 2010.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] On 3 November 2010, a high-definition simulcast of BBC One was launched, entitled BBC One HD, and BBC Two HD launched on 26 March 2013, replacing BBC HD.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Scotland's new television channel, BBC Scotland, launched in February 2019.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In the Republic of Ireland, Belgium, the Netherlands and Switzerland, the BBC channels are available in a number of ways.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In these countries digital and cable operators carry a range of BBC channels.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Since 1975 the BBC has also provided its TV programmes to the British Forces Broadcasting Service (BFBS), allowing members of UK military serving abroad to watch them on four dedicated TV channels.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] From 27 March 2013, BFBS will carry versions of BBC One and BBC Two, which will include children's programming from CBBC, as well as carrying programming from BBC Three on a new channel called BFBS Extra.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Since 2008 all BBC channels are available to watch online through the BBC iPlayer service.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] This online streaming ability came about following experiments with live streaming, involving streaming certain channels in the UK.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In February 2014, Director-General Tony Hall announced that the corporation needed to save £100 million.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In March 2014, the BBC confirmed plans for BBC Three to become an internet-only channel.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] An earlier ten months of listings are to be obtained from other sources.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] They identified about five million programmes, involving 8.5 million actors, presenters, writers and technical staff.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The Genome project was opened to public access on 15 October 2014, with corrections to OCR errors and changes to advertised schedules being crowdsourced.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC has ten radio stations serving the whole of the UK, a further seven stations in the "national regions" (Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland), and 39 other local stations serving defined areas of England.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Of the ten national stations, five are major stations and are available on FM or AM as well as on DAB and online.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In addition to these five stations, the BBC runs a further five stations that broadcast on DAB and online only.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] These stations supplement and expand on the big five stations, and were launched in 2002.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1Xtra sisters Radio 1, and broadcasts new Black music and urban tracks.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 5 Sports Extra sisters 5 Live and offers extra sport analysis, including broadcasting sports that previously were not covered.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 6 Music offers alternative music genres and is notable as a platform for new artists.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 7, later renamed BBC Radio 4 Extra, provides archive drama, comedy and children's programming.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The final station is the BBC Asian Network, providing music, talk and news to this section of the community.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] This station evolved out of Local radio stations serving certain areas, and as such this station is available on medium wave frequency in some areas of the Midlands.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] As well as the national stations, the BBC also provides 40 BBC Local Radio stations in England and the Channel Islands, each named for and covering a particular city and its surrounding area (e.g.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Bristol), county or region (e.g.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Three Counties Radio), or geographical area (e.g.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Radio Solent covering the central south coast).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] A further six stations broadcast in what the BBC terms "the national regions": Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] These are BBC Radio Wales (in English), BBC Radio Cymru (in Welsh), BBC Radio Scotland (in English), BBC Radio nan Gàidheal (in Scottish Gaelic), BBC Radio Ulster, and BBC Radio Foyle, the latter being an opt-out station from Radio Ulster for the north-west of Northern Ireland.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC's UK national channels are also broadcast in the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man (although these Crown Dependencies are outside the UK), and in the former there are two local stations – BBC Radio Guernsey and BBC Radio Jersey.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] There is no BBC local radio station, however, in the Isle of Man, partly because the island has long been served by the popular independent commercial station, Manx Radio, which predates the existence of BBC Local Radio.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC services in the dependencies are financed from television licence fees which are set at the same level as those payable in the UK, although collected locally.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] This is the subject of some controversy in the Isle of Man since, as well as having no BBC Local Radio service, the island also lacks a local television news service analogous to that provided by BBC Channel Islands.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It is broadcast worldwide on shortwave radio, DAB and online and has an estimated weekly audience of 192 million, and its websites have an audience of 38 million people per week.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Since 2005, it is also available on DAB in the UK, a step not taken before, due to the way it is funded.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Following the Government's spending review in 2011, the service was funded for the first time through the Licence fee.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In recent years, some services of the World Service have been reduced: the Thai service ended in 2006, as did the Eastern European languages.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Resources were diverted instead into the new BBC News Arabic.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Historically the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster based in the UK mainland until 1967, when University Radio York, then under the name *Radio York*, was launched as the first, and now oldest, legal independent radio station in the country.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] However, the BBC did not enjoy a complete monopoly before this, as several Continental stations, such as Radio Luxembourg, had broadcast programmes in English to Britain since the 1930s and the Isle of Man-based Manx Radio began in 1964.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Today, despite the advent of commercial broadcasting, BBC radio stations remain among the most listened-to in the country.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Radio 2 has the largest audience share (up to 16.8% in 2011–12) and Radios 1 and 4 ranked second and third in terms of weekly reach.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC programming is also available to other services and in other countries.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Since 1943, the BBC has provided radio programming to the British Forces Broadcasting Service, which broadcasts in countries where British troops are stationed.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Radio 1 is also carried in Canada on SiriusXM (online streaming only).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC is a patron of the Radio Academy, a registered UK charity that promotes excellence in broadcasting.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC News is the largest broadcast news gathering operation in the world, providing services to BBC domestic radio as well as television networks such as the BBC News, BBC Parliament and BBC News International.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In addition to this, news stories are available on the BBC Red Button service and BBC News Online.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In addition to this, the BBC has been developing new ways to access BBC News and as a result, has launched the service on BBC Mobile, making it accessible to mobile phones and PDAs, as well as developing alerts by email, on digital television, and on computers through a desktop alert.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Ratings figures suggest that during major incidents such as the 7 July 2005 London bombings or royal events, the UK audience overwhelmingly turns to the BBC's coverage as opposed to its commercial rivals.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] On 7 July 2005, the day there were a series of coordinated bomb blasts on London's public transport system, the BBC Online website recorded an all time bandwidth peak of 11 Gb/s at 12.00 on 7 July.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC News received some 1 billion total hits on the day of the event (including all images, text, and HTML), serving some 5.5 terabytes of data.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] At peak times during the day, there were 40,000-page requests per second for the BBC News website.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The previous day's announcement of the 2012 Summer Olympics being awarded to London caused a peak of about 5 Gbit/s.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The previous all-time high at BBC Online was caused by the announcement of the Michael Jackson verdict, which used 7.2 Gbit/s.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC's online presence includes a comprehensive news website and archive.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC's first official online service was the BBC Networking Club, which was launched on 11 May 1994.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The service was subsequently relaunched as BBC Online in 1997, before being renamed BBCi, then bbc.co.uk, before it was rebranded back as BBC Online.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The website is funded by the Licence fee, but uses GeoIP technology, allowing advertisements to be carried on the site when viewed outside of the UK.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC claims the site to be "Europe's most popular content-based site" and states that 13.2 million people in the UK visit the site's more than two million pages each day.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The centre of the website is the Homepage, which features a modular layout.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Users can choose which modules, and which information, is displayed on their homepage, allowing the user to customise it.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] This system was first launched in December 2007, becoming permanent in February 2008, and has undergone a few aesthetical changes since then.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The home page then has links to other micro-sites, such as BBC News Online, Sport, Weather, TV, and Radio.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] As part of the site, every programme on BBC Television or Radio is given its own page, with bigger programmes getting their own micro-site, and as a result it is often common for viewers and listeners to be told URLs for the programme website.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Also, through participation in the Creative Archive Licence group, bbc.co.uk allowed legal downloads of selected archive material via the internet.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC has often included learning as part of its online service, running services such as BBC Jam, Learning Zone Class Clips and also runs services such as BBC WebWise and First Click which are designed to teach people how to use the internet.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Jam was a free online service, delivered through broadband and narrowband connections, providing high-quality interactive resources designed to stimulate learning at home and at school.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Initial content was made available in January 2006; however, BBC Jam was suspended on 20 March 2007 due to allegations made to the European Commission that it was damaging the interests of the commercial sector of the industry.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In recent years some major on-line companies and politicians have complained that BBC Online receives too much funding from the television licence, meaning that other websites are unable to compete with the vast amount of advertising-free on-line content available on BBC Online.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Some have proposed that the amount of licence fee money spent on BBC Online should be reduced—either being replaced with funding from advertisements or subscriptions, or a reduction in the amount of content available on the site.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In response to this the BBC carried out an investigation, and has now set in motion a plan to change the way it provides its online services.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Online will now attempt to fill in gaps in the market, and will guide users to other websites for currently existing market provision.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] (For example, instead of providing local events information and timetables, users will be guided to outside websites already providing that information.) Part of this plan included the BBC closing some of its websites, and rediverting money to redevelop other parts.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] On 26 February 2010 *The Times* claimed that Mark Thompson, Director General of the BBC, proposed that the BBC's web output should be cut by 50%, with online staff numbers and budgets reduced by 25% in a bid to scale back BBC operations and allow commercial rivals more room.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] On 2 March 2010, the BBC reported that it would cut its website spending by 25% and close BBC 6 Music and Asian Network, as part of Mark Thompson's plans to make "a smaller, fitter BBC for the digital age".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Red Button is the brand name for the BBC's interactive television services, which are available through Freeview (digital terrestrial), as well as Freesat, Sky UK (satellite), and Virgin Media (cable).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Unlike Ceefax, the service's analogue counterpart, BBC Red Button is able to display full-colour graphics, photographs, and video, as well as programmes and can be accessed from any BBC channel.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The service carries News, Weather and Sport 24 hours a day, but also provides extra features related to programmes specific at that time.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Examples include viewers to play along at home to gameshows, to give, voice and vote on opinions to issues, as used alongside programmes such as *Question Time*.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] At some points in the year, when multiple sporting events occur, some coverage of less mainstream sports or games are frequently placed on the Red Button for viewers to watch.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Frequently, other features are added unrelated to programmes being broadcast at that time, such as the broadcast of the *Doctor Who* animated episode *Dreamland* in November 2009.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It also buys a selected number of broadcasts from the Ulster Orchestra in Belfast and the BBC Big Band.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC Proms have been produced by the BBC every year since 1927, stepping in to fund the popular eight-week summer classical music festival when music publishers Chappell and Co withdrew their support.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In 1930, the newly formed BBC Symphony Orchestra gave all 49 Proms, and have performed at every Last Night of the Proms since then.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The Proms have been held at the Royal Albert Hall since 1941, and the BBC's orchestras and choirs are the backbone of the festival, giving about 40% to 50% of all performances each season.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Many famous musicians of every genre have played at the BBC, such as The Beatles (*Live at the BBC* is one of their many albums).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC is also responsible for the broadcast of Glastonbury Festival, Reading and Leeds Festivals and United Kingdom coverage of the Eurovision Song Contest, a show with which the broadcaster has been associated for over 60 years.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC also operates the division of BBC Audiobooks sometimes found in association with Chivers Audiobooks.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC operates other ventures as well as its broadcasting arm.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In addition to broadcasting output on television and radio, some programmes are also displayed on the BBC Big Screens in several central-city locations.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC and the Foreign, Commonwealth and Development Office also jointly run BBC Monitoring, which monitors radio, television, the press and the internet worldwide.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The National Museum of Computing at Bletchley Park uses BBC Micros as part of a scheme to educate school children about computer programming.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In 1951, in conjunction with Oxford University Press, the BBC published *The BBC Hymn Book*, intended to be used by radio listeners to follow hymns being broadcast.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The book was published both with and without music, the music edition being entitled *The BBC Hymn Book with Music*.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC provided the world's first teletext service called Ceefax (near-homophonous with "See Facts") from 23 September 1974 until 23 October 2012 on the BBC1 analogue channel, then later on BBC2.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It showed informational pages, such as news, sport, and the weather.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] From New Year's Eve, 1974, ITV's Oracle tried to compete with Ceefax.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] During its lifetime, Ceefax attracted millions of viewers, right up until 2012, prior to the digital switchover in the United Kingdom.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Since then, the BBC's Red Button Service has provided a digital information system that replaced Ceefax.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In 2016 the BBC, in partnership with fellow UK broadcasters ITV and Channel 4 (the latter later withdrew from the project), set up 'project kangaroo' to develop an international online streaming service to rival services such as Netflix and Hulu.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] During the development stages 'Britflix' was touted as a potential name.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] However, the service eventually launched as BritBox in March 2017.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The online platform shows a catalogue of classic BBC and ITV shows, as well as making a number of programmes available shortly after their UK broadcast.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] As of 2021, BritBox is available in the UK, the US, Canada, Australia, and, more recently, South Africa, with the potential availability for new markets in the future.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Studios is the wholly owned commercial subsidiary of the BBC, responsible for the commercial exploitation of BBC programmes and other properties, including a number of television stations throughout the world.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It was formed in 2018 after the merger of the BBC's commercial production arm and the BBC's commercial international distribution arm, BBC Worldwide, with the latter formed in 1995 following the restructuring of its predecessor, BBC Enterprises.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Prior to this, the selling of BBC television programmes was at first handled in 1958 with the establishment of a business manager post.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] This expanded until the establishment of the Television Promotions (renamed Television Enterprises) department in 1960 under a general manager.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The company owns and administers a number of commercial stations around the world operating in a number of territories and on a number of different platforms.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] These include BBC UKTV for the Australasia region, and formerly BBC America (now fully owned by AMC Networks).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The company airs two channels aimed at children, an international CBeebies channel and BBC Kids, a joint venture with Knowledge Network Corporation.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The company also runs BBC Earth, which distributes the BBC's natural history content to countries outside the UK, and BBC Lifestyle, broadcasting programmes based on themes of Food, Style and Wellbeing.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In addition to this, BBC Studios ran an international version of the channel BBC HD.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also distributes the 24-hour international news channel BBC News.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The station is separate from BBC Studios to maintain the station's neutral point of view, but is distributed by BBC Studios.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The channel itself is the oldest surviving entity of its kind, and has 50 foreign news bureaus and correspondents in nearly all countries in the world.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] As officially surveyed, it is available to more than 294 million households, significantly more than CNN's estimated 200 million.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In addition to these international channels, BBC Studios also owns the UKTV network of seven channels.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] These channels contain BBC archive programming to be rebroadcast on their respective channels: Alibi, crime dramas; Dave (slogan: "The Home of Witty Banter"); Drama, drama, launched in 2013; Eden, nature; Gold, comedy; W, Entertainment; and Yesterday, history programming.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In addition to these channels, many BBC programmes are sold via BBC Studios to foreign television stations with comedy, documentaries, crime dramas (such as *Luther* and *Peaky Blinders*) and historical drama productions being the most popular.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC's most successful reality television show format, *Strictly Come Dancing*—under the title *Dancing with the Stars*—has been exported to 60 other countries.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Shows commissioned and distributed by the BBC include the *Wallace & Gromit* animated comedy short films *The Wrong Trousers* and *A Close Shave*.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC television news also appears nightly on many PBS stations in the US, as do reruns of BBC programmes such as *EastEnders*, and in New Zealand on TVNZ 1.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In addition to programming, BBC Studios produces material to accompany programmes.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The company maintained the publishing arm of the BBC, BBC Magazines, which published the *Radio Times*; first published by the BBC on 28 September 1923, it is the world's first broadcast listings magazine.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] *Radio Times* covers all British television and radio programming schedules, and the 1988 Christmas edition sold 11,220,666 copies, which the *Guinness World Records* certified as the biggest-selling edition of any British magazine in history.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Other magazines that support BBC programming include *BBC Top Gear*, *BBC Good Food*, *BBC Sky at Night*, *BBC History*, *BBC Wildlife* and *BBC Music*.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Magazines was sold to Exponent Private Equity in 2011, which merged it with Origin Publishing (previously owned by BBC Worldwide between 2004 and 2006) to form Immediate Media Company.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] BBC Studios also publishes books, to accompany programmes such as *Sherlock* and *Doctor Who* under the BBC Books brand, a publishing imprint majority owned by Random House.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Archive programming and classical music recordings are sold under the brand BBC Legends.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Until the development, popularisation, and domination of television, radio was the broadcast medium upon which people in the United Kingdom relied.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It "reached into every home in the land, and simultaneously united the nation, an important factor during the Second World War".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC introduced the world's first "high-definition" 405-line television service in 1936.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It suspended its television service during the Second World War and until 1946, but remained the only television broadcaster in the UK until 1955, when Independent Television (ITV) began operating.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] This heralded the transformation of television into a popular and dominant medium.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Nevertheless, "throughout the 1950s radio still remained the dominant source of broadcast comedy".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Further, the BBC was the only legal radio broadcaster until 1968 (when University Radio York obtained its first licence).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Despite the advent of commercial television and radio, with competition from ITV, Channel 4 and Sky, the BBC has remained one of the main elements in British popular culture through its obligation to produce TV and radio programmes for mass audiences.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] However, the arrival of BBC2 allowed the BBC also to make programmes for minority interests in drama, documentaries, current affairs, entertainment, and sport.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Described as television's first "watercooler moment" by *The Telegraph*, the BBC's 1954 adaptation of *Nineteen Eighty-Four* made a dramatic impact on a fledgling television audience who were horrified by the graphic depiction of a totalitarian regime controlling the population.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Making his BBC debut in 1949, Benny Hill with *The Benny Hill Show* became the first British comedian to become famous via television.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Popular comedy duos on the BBC include Morecambe and Wise (whose show debuted in 1968) and The Two Ronnies (debuting in 1971).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Black comedy sitcom *Blackadder*, starring Rowan Atkinson as the title character, ran for four series between 1983 and 1989.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The British Academy Film Awards (BAFTAs) was first broadcast on the BBC in 1956, with Vivien Leigh as the host.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The television equivalent, the British Academy Television Awards, has been screened exclusively on the BBC since a 2007 awards ceremony that included wins for Jim Broadbent (Best actor) and Ricky Gervais (Best comedy performance).
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The term "BBC English" was used as an alternative name for Received Pronunciation, and the *English Pronouncing Dictionary* uses the term "BBC Pronunciation" to label its recommendations.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] However, the BBC itself now makes more use of regional accents to reflect the diversity of the UK, while continuing to expect clarity and fluency of its presenters.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] From its "starchy" beginnings, the BBC has also become more inclusive, and now attempts to accommodate the interests of all strata of society and all minorities, because they all pay the licence fee.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Older domestic UK audiences often refer to the BBC as "the Beeb", a nickname coined by Peter Sellers during a 1972 reunion of the 1950s BBC radio comedy *The Goon Show*, when he referred to the "Beeb Beeb Ceeb".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It was then shortened and popularised by radio DJ Kenny Everett.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] David Bowie's recording sessions at the BBC were released as *Bowie at the Beeb*, while Queen's BBC recording sessions were released as *At the Beeb*.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The term "Auntie" for the BBC is often credited to radio disc-jockey Jack Jackson.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] To celebrate the fiftieth anniversary of the BBC the song "Auntie" was released in 1972.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It also featured in the title of the BBC's blooper show, *Auntie's Bloomers*, which was presented by Terry Wogan from 1991 to 2001.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The two nicknames have also been used together as "Auntie Beeb".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Throughout its existence the BBC has faced numerous accusations regarding many topics: the Iraq war, the Gaza war, politics, ethics and religion, as well as funding and staffing.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It also has been involved in numerous controversies because of its coverage of specific news stories and programming.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC has been accused repeatedly of anti-Israel bias, and to a greater extent anti-Israel Defense Force bias.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC has long faced accusations of liberal and left-wing bias.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Accusations of a bias against the Premiership of Margaret Thatcher and the Conservative Party were often made against the BBC by members of that government, with Margaret Thatcher herself considering the broadcaster's news coverage to be biased and irresponsible.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In 2011, Peter Sissons, a main news presenter at the BBC from 1989 to 2009, said that "at the core of the BBC, in its very DNA, is a way of thinking that is firmly of the Left".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Another BBC presenter, Andrew Marr, commented that "the BBC is not impartial or neutral.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It has a liberal bias, not so much a party-political bias.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] It is better expressed as a cultural liberal bias." Former BBC director Roger Mosey classified it as "liberal defensive".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In 2022, the BBC chairman, Richard Sharp, said that the BBC "does have a liberal bias" and that the institution is "fighting against it".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In November 2025, allegations by *The Daily Telegraph* that the BBC had deceptively spliced a Donald Trump speech preceding the January 6 United States Capitol attack in a documentary led to several BBC executives resigning, including the head of the BBC.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Writing for *The Guardian* in 2018, the left-wing columnist Owen Jones stated "the truth is the BBC is stacked full of rightwingers," and cited as an example of bias its employment of "ultra-Thatcherite" Andrew Neil as a politics presenter.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] In November 2025, LibDem leader Ed Davey called for Gibb's removal from the BBC board because of Gibb's alleged role in the 2025 BBC editorial bias controversy.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] A 2018 opinion poll by BMG Research found that 40% of the British public thought that the BBC was politically partisan, with a nearly even split between those who believed it leaned to the left or right.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Additionally oft-cited are its policy of "balancing" appearances by transgender people with activists from gender-critical groups, its manual of style which requires any allegations of transphobia to be challenged by the news presenter, and its policy against using the term "cisgender".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] The BBC has also been accused by gender-critical groups and BBC staff of having a pro-trans bias, primarily for "failing to make it clear that transgender women are biological males".
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Such accusations have alleged that the BBC's LGBT desk has been "captured by a small group of people" intent on promoting a pro-trans agenda.
[src:british-deaf-association/bbc-p02] Shortly thereafter, the BBC began running articles referring to trans women as "biological males who identify as women".
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] The **British Deaf Association** (**BDA**) is a deaf-led British charity that campaigns and advocates for deaf people who use British Sign Language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] It was preceded by the National Association for the Deaf and Dumb (NADD), which had been founded by deaf people in 1886.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] The creation of the NADD had been in response to the perceived threats to the language and education rights of deaf people which had arisen after the Milan Conference of 1880.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] This international congress, where the majority of those attending were people who taught hearing to deaf children, had passed a resolution banning the use of sign languages throughout the world.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] The participants of the conference had then returned to their home countries, determined to eradicate both the employment of deaf teachers and the use of sign language in schools.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] They also sought to reduce class sizes to those that were manageable by hearing teachers.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] In 1889, the NADD ceased to exist and so four deaf men, including Francis Maginn and George Healey, arranged a meeting in January 1890 at St.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] Saviour's Church for the Deaf, Oxford Street, London, that they called the "National Conference of Adult Deaf and Dumb Missions and Associations".
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] The conference considered the forming of a national society to "elevate the education and social status of the Deaf and Dumb in the United Kingdom" and resulted in the formation of the British Deaf and Dumb Association (BDDA) in Leeds on 24 July 1890.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] The BDDA deleted the world "Dumb" from its title in 1971.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] It wasn't until the 1970s that schools began to look again at accepting sign language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] The advent of sign language and its acceptance by the general public resulted in deaf leaders slowly coming back to the forefront starting with Jock Young as the first deaf chair in 1983 and, in the mid-1990s, its first deaf chief executive, Jeff McWhinney.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] In the 1990s the BDA became a deaf-led organisation and the campaigning for the recognition of sign language is to date the main focus of their work.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] Previous Chairs include the late Terry Riley, editor of the BBC's *See Hear* programme.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] In 2003, the BDA released a document describing various steps for public services to improve accessibility for Deaf people and BSL users, called the 'BSL Charter'.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] In 2017, the BDA released an updated version of the charter called the Charter for British Sign Language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-deaf-association] The Mayor of London, Sadiq Khan, signed the charter in November 2023.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 2016 the British Deaf Association (BDA) said that, based on official statistics, it believes there are 151,000 people who use BSL in the UK, and 87,000 of these are deaf.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] This figure does not include professional BSL users, interpreters, translators, etc. unless they use BSL at home.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] By contrast, in the 2011 England and Wales Census 15,000 people living in England and Wales reported themselves using BSL as their main language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In Northern Ireland, there are about 4,500 users of BSL and 1,500 users of Irish Sign Language, an unrelated sign language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] A hybrid version, dubbed "Northern Ireland Sign Language", is also used.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] On 18 March 2003 the UK government formally recognised BSL as a language in its own right.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 2022, the British Sign Language Act was passed, which legally recognised BSL as a language of England, Wales and Scotland.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] BSL is used in some educational establishments, but is not always the policy for deaf children in some local authority areas.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] As of January 2026, there is no GCSE qualification in British Sign Language available to students, but one is under development in England and planned for Wales.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The Department for Education began to develop the GCSE in 2019, but the process was delayed due to the Covid-19 pandemic.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In June 2023, the UK Government launched a consultation for the GCSE, with teaching initially planned to begin in schools from September 2025.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 2024, Qualifications Wales suspended development of its GCSE in BSL, setting a new goal to introduce it to schools in Wales in 2027.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 2025, Ofqual ran a second consultation to gather feedback on its proposed rules for the qualification in England, releasing the results and its final decisions on the rules in November.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] GCSE exam boards who want to run the qualification in England must next make detailed offers to Ofqual for accreditation based on these regulations.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Many British television channels broadcast programmes with in-vision signing, using BSL, as well as specially made programmes aimed mainly at deaf people such as the BBC's *See Hear* and Channel 4's *VEE-TV*.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] There is also a specially dedicated British Sign Language channel, LumoTV (previously BSL Zone), established in 2008.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] All BBC channels (excluding BBC One and BBC Alba) provide in-vision signing for some of their programmes.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] BBC Two also broadcasts in-vision signed repeats of the main channel's primetime programmes between 00:00 and 05:00 each weekday and early Saturday mornings.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] It also provides signing on weekday mornings between 08:00 and 09:00.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 2024, over 10% of Channel 4's programming was signed, including popular shows such as Hollyoaks and Gogglebox.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Published in 1992, the British Sign Language Dictionary was compiled for the British Deaf Association by the Deaf Studies Research Unit at the University of Durham.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The dictionary was edited by David Brien, assisted by a team composed by Mary Brennan, Clark Denmark, Frances Elton, Liz Scott Gibson, Graham Turner and Dorothy Miles, among others.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] It depicts over 1,800 signs through pictures and diagrams, each sign accompanied by definitions, explanations and usage.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The signs are ordered not alphabetically, as a dictionary of the English language, but rather according to the phonological characteristics of the language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] For example, signs that are based on the "fist" handshape come before signs based on the "open hand" handshape.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The foreword was written by Diana, Princess of Wales, who was the patron of the BDA.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Corpus Project, based at the Deafness Cognition and Language Research Centre (University College London), was funded between 2008 and 2011 to provide a video corpus of BSL in four regions (Bristol, Birmingham, London and Manchester).
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] It was succeeded by the BSL SignBank, which moved the BSL Corpus online between 2011 and 2015.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] It also draws on the 1992 BSL Dictionary for its vocabulary.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Certain signs used in Scotland, for example, may not be understood immediately, or not understood at all, by those in Southern England, or vice versa.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Some signs are even more local, occurring only in certain towns or cities (such as the Manchester system of number signs).
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Likewise, some may go in or out of fashion, or evolve over time, just as terms in oral languages do.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Families may have signs unique to them to accommodate for certain situations or to describe an object that may otherwise require fingerspelling.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Although the United Kingdom and the United States share English as the predominant spoken language, British Sign Language is quite distinct from American Sign Language (ASL), having only 31% signs identical, or 44% cognate.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Irish Sign Language (ISL), which is more closely related to French Sign Language (LSF) and ASL.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Signed English, a manually coded method expressed to represent the English language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The sign languages used in Australia and New Zealand, Auslan and New Zealand Sign Language respectively, evolved largely from 19th century BSL, and all retain the same manual alphabet and grammar and possess similar lexicons.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The sign language used in Sri Lanka is also closely related to BSL despite the oral language not being English, demonstrating variation in distance between sign languages and spoken ones.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] While private correspondence from William Stokoe hinted at a formal name for the language in 1960, the first usage of the term "British Sign Language" in an academic publication was likely by Aaron Cicourel.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The earliest known document describing the use of signing in a legal context is dated to c.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] 1324 and mentions John de Orleton, a deaf man assigning his property to a family member.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Published in 1450, the *History of the Syon Monastery at Lisbon and Brentford*, contains descriptions of signs—some of which are still in use.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The earliest evidence of signing in registry records is from a marriage ceremony between a deaf man, Thomas Tilsye and Ursula Russel on 6 February 1576 at St Martin's Church, now Leicester Cathedral.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Richard Carew's *Survey of Cornwall* (1602) includes a description of Edward Bone, a deaf servant, meeting his deaf friend John Kempe.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Bone had some knowledge of Cornish and was able to lipread, but appeared to prefer signing.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In particular, *Chirologia* focuses on the meanings of gestures, expressions and body language, and describes signs and gestures in use at the time, some of which resemble signs still in use, while *Philocopus* explores the use of lipreading by deaf people and the possibility of deaf education.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Another writer of the same time, George Dalgarno, recognised that sign language was unrelated to English.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] British Sign Language has evolved, as all languages do, from these origins by modification, invention and importation.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Thomas Braidwood, a teacher from Edinburgh, founded 'Braidwood's Academy for the Deaf and Dumb' in 1760, which is believed to be the first school for deaf children in Britain.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The school primarily taught oral communication, however there is evidence of 'deaf signing' being used as a teaching method (albeit probably following the structure of English).
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] This *combined system* came to be known as the English method—a sort of midway point between French manualist and German oralist systems, and was the first codification of what would later develop into British Sign Language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Joseph Watson was trained as a teacher of the deaf under Thomas Braidwood.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] He eventually left in 1792 to become the headmaster of the Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb in Bermondsey where he advocated for 'natural signing'—likely referring to the way deaf children naturally sign, as opposed to following English structure.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] This 'natural signing' is thought to be the precursor to modern BSL.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 1815 when Thomas Gallaudet visited England, the Braidwood school refused to teach him their methods unless he paid them.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] So instead, Gallaudet found himself in Paris, having been invited there by the much more accommodating Abbé Sicard.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Gallaudet would eventually take much of the what had learnt in France, back to the United States.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] As a consequence American Sign Language (ASL) today has a 60% similarity to modern French Sign Language and is almost unintelligible to users of British Sign Language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] By the mid 1800s, sign was the most prominent mode of communication within deaf schools in Britain, and by 1870, there were 22 (often residential) schools found in most major cities around the country.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The Second International Congress on Education of the Deaf, also known as the Milan Conference, was held in 1880, and proscribed the use of sign language in education; for the best part of a century, sign language was no longer used in the education of deaf children.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Signing was actively discouraged in schools by punishment, and deaf education emphasised teaching deaf children to learn to lip read and finger spell, due to the prevailing belief across Europe established that signing was bad.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Since there was no (or very little) exchange of sign language within educational establishments, signing was preserved through deaf clubs or within families.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Until the 1940s, sign language skills were passed between deaf people without a unified sign language system and many deaf people lived in residential institutions.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 1978, the government-issued Warnock Report advocated for the mainstreaming of deaf children which led to the closure of many deaf schools.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] During this time, the Total Communication method was popularised.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] From the 1970s there has been an increasing tolerance for the language, in part due to its recognition as a natural language by linguists.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In the 1980s, BSL started to be used as language of instruction in schools again, alongside English.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] This decade saw the start of deaf programming on British television.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Deaf scholar and activist Paddy Ladd is credited with getting sign language on television and enabling deaf children to be educated in sign.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] BSL users campaigned to have BSL recognised on an official level.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 mandates the provision of interpreters.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 1999, the Federation of Deaf People (FDP) led a 4000-strong march in London to demand the recognition of BSL as a language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] This can be considered to mark the first political march by the modern 'British Deaf Community', as an established community.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Let Sign Shine is a campaign started by Norfolk teenager Jade Chapman, whose sister is deaf, to raise awareness of BSL and to petition for BSL to be taught in schools.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The campaign's petition to Parliament attracted support from over four thousand people.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Chapman won awards for her work including the education award category at the Bernard Matthews Youth Award 2014 for her work in raising awareness of the importance of sign language.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Having been donated £1,000 from the Bernard Matthews Youth Award, Let Sign Shine used this to start a British Sign Language course at Dereham Neatherd High School.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 2021, MP Rosie Cooper (a CODA) introduced the British Sign Language Bill to recognise BSL, this time as an official language (not merely its existence as had been done in 2003), which was backed by the government.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] After being dormant from June 2021, the bill began moving through Parliament on 28 January 2022, but during a meeting with stakeholders on 7 February, the language of the bill was revealed to have been pared down substantially, disappointing said stakeholders.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The British Deaf Association stated that it was 'unhappy' with this removal of language from the bill.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Act received royal assent on 28th April 2022.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Linguistics is the study of language, including those like BSL that are not carried by sound.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In all sign languages the great majority of 'words' (hand gestures) cannot be understood in other sign languages.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] How one language signs a certain number would be different from how another language signs it.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The way sentences are constructed (syntax) differs from sign language to sign language, just as with different spoken languages.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] British Sign Language is described as a 'spatial language' as it "moves signs in space".
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Like many other sign languages, BSL phonology is defined by elements such as handshape, orientation, location, movement, and non-manual features.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] There are phonological components to sign language that have no meaning alone but work together to create a meaning of a signed word: hand shape, movement, location, orientation and facial expression.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The meanings of words differ if one of these components is changed.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Signs can be identical in certain components but different in others, giving each a different meaning.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Facial expression falls under the nonmanual feature component of phonology.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In common with other languages, whether spoken or signed, BSL has its own grammar which govern how phrases are signed.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] One important component of BSL is its use of proforms.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] A proform is "...any form that stands in the place of, or does the job of, some other form." Sentences are composed of two parts, in order: the subject and the predicate.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The subject is the topic of the sentence, while the predicate is the commentary about the subject.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Question words are generally at the end of a sentence.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Topic-comment means that the topic of the signed conversation is first established, followed by an elaboration of the topic, being the 'comment' component.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The canonical word order outside of the topic–comment structure is object–subject–verb (OSV), and noun phrases are head-initial.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The language continues to evolve as older signs such as *alms* and *pawnbroker* have fallen out of use and new signs such as *internet* and *laser* have been coined.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The evolution of the language and its changing level of acceptance meant that older users tend to use more finger spelling while younger ones make use of a wider range of signs.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] In 2019, over 100 signs for scientific terms, including 'deoxyribonucleotide' and 'deoxyribonucleoside', were added to BSL, after being conceived by Liam Mcmulkin, a deaf graduate of the University of Dundee, who had found finger-spelling such words tiresome, during his degree course.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Similarly, architects Chris Laing and Adolfs Kristapsons developed a project called SignStrokes which developed new signs for the built environment, having not wanted to continuously make new signs for different architectural concepts.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] British Sign Language can be learnt from formal institutions throughout the UK and three examination systems exist.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Courses are provided by community colleges, local centres for deaf people and private organisations.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] A teaching qualification programme was started by the British Deaf Association in 1984 at the University of Durham, called BSL Tutor Training Course, which closed in 1999.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] National awarding organisations run training for BSL teachers.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Each of these organisations has its own curriculum, teaching materials and resources.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] There are two qualification routes: via post-graduate studies, or via National Vocational Qualifications.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Deaf studies undergraduate courses with specific streams for sign language interpreting exist at several British universities; post-graduate level interpreting diplomas are also on offer from universities and one private company.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Course entry requirements vary from no previous knowledge of BSL to NVQ level 6 BSL (or equivalent).
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The qualification process allows interpreters to register with the National Registers of Communication Professionals with Deaf and Deafblind People (NRCPD), a voluntary regulator.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Registrants are asked to self-certify that they have both cleared a DBS (Disclosure and Barring Service) check and are covered by professional indemnity insurance.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Completing a level 3 BSL language assessment and enrolling on an approved interpreting course allows applications to register as a TSLI (Trainee Sign Language Interpreter).
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] After completing an approved interpreting course, trainees can then apply to achieve RSLI (Registered Sign Language Interpreter) status.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] RSLIs are currently required by NRCPD to log Continuous Professional Development activities.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Post-qualification, specialist training is still considered necessary to work in specific critical domains.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] Communication support workers (CSWs) are professionals who support the communication of deaf students in education at all ages, and deaf people in many areas of work, using British Sign Language and other communication methods such as Sign Supported English.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] The qualifications and experience of CSWs vary: some are fully qualified interpreters, others are not.
[src:british-deaf-association/british-sign-language] There are currently two well-established BSL language learning apps and web platforms: Bright BSL and Lingvano.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The **Charity Commission for England and Wales** (Welsh: *Comisiwn Elusennau Cymru a Lloegr*) is the statutory regulator of registered charities in England and Wales.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] It maintains the public register of charities and oversees compliance with charity law.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Commission is a non-ministerial department of His Majesty's Government that regulates registered charities in England and Wales and maintains the **Central Register of Charities**.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Its counterparts in Scotland and Northern Ireland are the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator and the Charity Commission for Northern Ireland.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission has four sites in London, Taunton, Liverpool and Newport.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Its website lists the latest annual reports submitted by charities in England and Wales.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] During the financial year 2022–2023, the Commission regulated £88 billion of charity income and £85 billion of charity spend.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] To establish a charity, an organisation must first find at least three trustees who will be responsible for the general control and management of the administration of the charity.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The organisation needs to have a charitable purpose that helps the public.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Afterwards, the administration must select an official name and decide on a structure for the charity that will impact aspects such as who runs the charity and how it is run.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Subsequently, the creation of a governing document that explains how the charity is run is required.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Finally, an electronic application must be completed if the charity’s income is at £5,000 per year, or it is a charitable incorporated organisation (CIO).
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] There are different rules for creating a charity in Scotland and Northern Ireland.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Some charities are not subject to regulation by or registration with the Charity Commission, because they are already regulated by another body, and are known as exempt charities.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Most exempt charities are listed in Schedule 3 to the Charities Act 2011, but some charities are made exempt by other acts.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] However exempt charities must still comply with charity law and may approach the Charity Commission for advice.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Some charities are 'excepted' from charity registration.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This means they do not have to register or submit annual returns, but are in all other respects subject to regulation by the Charity Commission.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Registration of a charity in England and Wales does not endow that status elsewhere, thus further registration has to be made before operating in Scotland or Northern Ireland.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Charities in Scotland are regulated by the Office of the Scottish Charity Regulator.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In Northern Ireland the Charity Commission for Northern Ireland was established in 2009 to replace earlier regulation by the Voluntary and Community Unit of the Department for Social Development, part of the Northern Ireland Executive.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The principles of good governance, to be followed by charities in order for them to be able to achieve and maintain charitable status, are laid down in the Charity Governance Code, published by the Charity Governance Code Steering Group.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] There are two separate codes for small and large charities.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charity Commission is not part of the Charity Governance Code Steering Group; it is only an observer, to ensure impartiality.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Depending on how serious the complaint is, the Charity Commission will either recommend procedural improvements, require the expulsion of unsuitable trustees, or remove the organisation's charitable status altogether.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charities Act 2006 requires the Commission to be operationally independent of ministerial influence or control.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Members of the commission, including the chair, are appointed by the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Finance Act 2010 extended charitable tax benefits (for example Gift Aid) to charities within EU member states, Norway and Iceland, rather than those just inside the UK.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In 2016, following the Olive Cooke scandal, British fundraising regulations were reviewed.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This led to the establishment of the Fundraising Regulator.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Fundraising Regulator is an independent oversight body without statutory authority.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] It defines and promotes fundraising standards, investigates cases, addresses public complaints about fundraising practices, and operates a fundraising preference service that allows the public to control how charities contact them.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission carries out general monitoring of charities as part of its regular casework.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In serious cases of abuse and regulatory concern, the commission has powers outlined in the Charities Acts to conduct statutory investigations.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Before taking the decision to open a statutory inquiry, it will take the approach set out in its Regulatory and Risk framework.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission, therefore, began around 2007 to carry out an intermediate form of action described as regulatory compliance investigations.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In 2010 it opened over 140 of these cases, compared to just three full statutory investigations.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] However, the legality of these actions was debatable as they lacked a statutory basis.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] A high-profile example was the commission's report into The Atlantic Bridge, after which that body was dissolved in September 2011.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission announced in October 2011, in the context of cost-cutting and a re-focussing of its activities, that it would no longer carry out regulatory compliance investigations.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] In 2012, the commission refused to grant charitable status to Plymouth Brethren Christian Church, stating that it was unclear whether the body's aims were compatible with the requirement for charities to have a public benefit.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission stated that this was called into doubt as a result of the "exclusivity" of the body.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The decision was discussed at a session of the Public Accounts Committee, during which MP Charlie Elphicke accused the commission of being "committed to the suppression of religion".
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The decision was later reversed by the Commission.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Between 2022 and 2023, the commission removed 4,146 charities from the register and concluded 5,726 regulatory action cases (includes 68 statutory inquiries).
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Prior to the 1840s, a body of commissioners had been established by the Statute of Charitable Uses 1601 (43 Eliz.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charity Commission was first established by the Charitable Trusts Act 1853.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] There had been several attempts at reforming charities before that which had been opposed by various interest groups including the church, the courts, the companies, and the universities.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The power of the commission was strengthened by amendments to the act in 1855, 1860, and 1862.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charity Commission was substantially reconstituted by the Charities Act 1960 (8 & 9 Eliz.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] 58), which replaced the Charitable Trusts Acts (1853-1891).
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This introduced new duties to determine charitable status, and to maintain a public register of charities.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The commission was criticised after the Aberfan disaster in 1966 for its intransigence and decisions on what it allowed money from the disaster fund to be spent on.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] It sanctioned the use of £150,000 to remove remaining spoil tips from the area after the National Coal Board refused to pay for the work.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] It also proposed asking parents 'exactly how close were you to your child?'; those found not to have been close to their children would not be compensated.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Charities Act 2006 established its current structure and name.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] As of 31 March 2015 the commission had 288 employees and 19 agency staff in post.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] The Olive Cooke case, involving a 92-year-old poppy seller who allegedly committed suicide due to overwhelming requests for donations from charities, sparked widespread public fear and media attention across England and Wales.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This scandal prompted a review of the self-regulation of fundraising practices in England and Wales, as well as Scotland, subsequently leading to the introduction of self-regulatory reforms in both jurisdictions.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Orlando Fraser was appointed as chair of the Charity Commission by the Secretary of State on a three-year term commencing from 25 April 2022.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] This appointment was not without controversy, including the refusal of the Digital, Culture, Media and Sports Committee to endorse the appointment.
[src:british-deaf-association/charity-commission-for-england-and-wales] Chief charity commissioner – prior to restructuring in 2006, the equivalent of the chair was the chief charity commissioner.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] In a medical context, deafness is defined as a degree of hearing difficulties such that a person is unable to understand speech, even in the presence of amplification.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] In profound deafness, even the loudest sounds produced by an audiometer (an instrument used to measure hearing by producing pure tone sounds through a range of frequencies) may not be perceived by the person.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] In total deafness, no sounds at all, regardless of amplification or method of production, can be heard.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Neurologically, language is processed in the same brain areas whether one is deaf or hearing.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The left hemisphere of the brain processes linguistic patterns whether by signed languages or by spoken languages.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] All of these forms of hearing loss impair a person's hearing; they are unable to perceive or interpret sounds correctly.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] These different types of hearing loss occur in different parts of the ear, which makes it difficult for the information heard to reach the brain properly.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] For each of these types, there are four different levels or amounts of hearing loss.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] This is when someone can still hear noises, but it is more difficult to hear the softer sounds.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The second level is *moderate hearing loss*, and this is when someone can hear almost nothing when someone is talking to them at a normal volume.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] *Severe hearing loss* is when someone can not hear any sounds when they are being produced at a normal level, and they can only hear minimal sounds that are being produced at a loud level.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The final level is *profound hearing loss*, which is when someone is not able to hear any sounds except for very loud ones.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Millions of people globally live with deafness or hearing impairments.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The 2005 Survey of Income and Program Participation (SIPP) indicated that fewer than 1 in 20 Americans are deaf or hard of hearing (DHH) at a level that makes normal conversations difficult to hear; more than half of these people are over retirement age.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Several solutions are available for many people with hearing impairments.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Additionally, people may use devices that use blinking lights instead of noises for alarm clocks or other notifications.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Cochlear implants are an option for children and adults with severe or profound hearing loss.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Cochlear implants are surgically placed devices that stimulate the cochlear nerve to help the person hear.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] A cochlear implant is used instead of hearing aids to help when someone has difficulties understanding speech.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] For children, the younger they are at the time of implantation, the better their auditory skill and perception.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Babies with confirmed bilateral profound sensorineural hearing loss may begin the surgical evaluation process for implantation as early as six months, with the US officially allowing the surgery to take place as early as nine months of age.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Children with other medical problems or other types of hearing loss may be considered at a slightly older age.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Parents sometimes have difficulty deciding to get cochlear implants for their child.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Many felt a sense of urgency, and, in the end, most parents felt it was beneficial for their child.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] In a cultural context, Deaf culture refers to a tight-knit cultural group of people whose primary language is signed, and who practice social and cultural norms which are distinct from those of the surrounding hearing community.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] This community does not automatically include all those who are clinically or legally deaf, nor does it exclude every hearing person.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] According to Baker and Padden, it includes any person who "identifies him/herself as a member of the Deaf community, and other members accept that person as a part of the community", an example being children of deaf adults with normal hearing ability.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] It includes the set of social beliefs, behaviors, art, literary traditions, history, values, and shared institutions of communities influenced by deafness and use sign languages as the main means of communication.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] While deafness is often included within the umbrella of disability, members of the Deaf community tend to view deafness as a difference in human experience or as a language minority.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Many non-disabled people incorrectly assume that deaf people have no autonomy.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] As children, deaf people learn literacy differently from hearing children.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] They learn to speak and write, whereas hearing children naturally learn to speak and eventually learn to write.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The Quota International organization, headquartered in the United States, provided considerable educational support in the Philippines, where it began offering free education to deaf children in the Leganes Resource Center for the Deaf.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The British organisation Sounds Seekers also supported deaf communities by offering audiology maintenance technology in hard-to-reach areas.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The Nippon Foundation supports deaf students at Gallaudet University and the National Technical Institute for the Deaf through international scholarship programs to encourage them to become future leaders in the deaf community.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] These organizations hope to provide opportunities and resources for the deaf community, and hope that they can help society build a more inclusive and tolerant environment for future generations.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The first known record of sign language in history comes from Plato's Cratylus, written in the fifth century BCE.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] In 1760, French philanthropic educator Charles-Michel de l'Épée opened the world's first free school for the deaf.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The school won approval for government funding in 1791 and became known as the "Institution Nationale des Sourds-Muets à Paris".
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Parents of deaf and hard-of-hearing children often encounter difficulties when choosing an educational setting for their child.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] They may consider the child's needs and abilities, how the school can accommodate the child, and the school environment itself.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] Both the child and the parent may benefit from trial and error with different schools, to identify the best available environment.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] There are two major paths available to deaf students.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] One option is to attend a public, non-specialized school, the same as they would if they were hearing.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] If the student is mainstreamed, they may use an interpreter in class, wear hearing aids, or other accommodations.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] The second option is to attend a specialized Deaf school.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] In America, most states have at least one.
[src:british-deaf-association/deafness] These are often boarding schools, and students will come from all over the state to attend.
[src:british-deaf-association/doug-alker] After leaving RNID Alker set up the radical political pressure group Federation of Deaf People (FDP) in 1998.
[src:british-deaf-association/doug-alker] As the chair, he and the FDP are primarily responsible for pressuring the UK government into officially recognizing British Sign Language.
[src:british-deaf-association/doug-alker] The FDP organised a 4000-strong march to Trafalgar Square in 1999 demanding the recognition of BSL.
[src:british-deaf-association/doug-alker] The march also delivered a petition to 10 Downing Street with 30,000 signatures backing the cause.
[src:british-deaf-association/doug-alker] On 18 March 2003 the UK government formally recognized that BSL is a language in its own right.
[src:british-deaf-association/doug-alker] He previously worked as a researcher for the BBC television programme *See Hear*.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Maginn was born in Mallow, County Cork, Ireland in 1861.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] His father was a Church of Ireland vicar, and his mother was well-connected to wealthy families in Ireland.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] His uncle William Maginn was a journalist who amongst other achievements co-founded and was a notable supporter of Fraser's Magazine.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] At the age of 5, he was about to be sent to Christ's Hospital (a famous boarding school in England), however he became deaf that year due to scarlet fever and his parents sent him to the Royal London Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb, which was on Old Kent Road at that time.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Maginn excelled at school and was offered a junior teachership at 17 in the Royal London Asylum's Margate Branch.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] He kept this position for five years, returned to Ireland for a year, and then went to the National Deaf-Mute College (later known as Gallaudet University) in Washington, DC.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] The move from Ireland to America had a profound effect on Maginn, who felt he now had the ability to achieve a higher level of attainment.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] He spent three years at Gallaudet and did not graduate because he had to leave to be at his father's bedside, but he left highly regarded and with letters of support (he received an honorary degree from Gallaudet in later life).
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Leaving Gallaudet, Maginn felt that the British approach to deafness was one of injustice, and that his life's work would be to enhance the quality of life for deaf in the United Kingdom.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Maginn returned to Ireland in 1882, he wanted to identify a potential springboard to establish a national association and he joined the Deaf and Dumb Correspondence Association, which was led by some influential deaf people of that time.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] The first attempt to establish an association, the Deaf-Mute Association was formed on 1 February 1888 to 'further the cause of the deaf and dumb' but it was short-lived.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] There were 239 members recruited into its membership, but, due to insufficient numbers, the association closed in 1889.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Despite the closure of the association, Francis Maginn and James Paul, a missioner and founder of the National Deaf and Dumb Society, were funded to attend the event marking 100 years anniversary of the death of a French educator and "Father of the Deaf" Charles-Michel de l'Épée.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] They made a pact on the train journey to Paris, France, to re-establish a national association and, by the time they arrived in Calais on the way home, the British delegates lent their support.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] The UK Royal Commission for the Blind, the Deaf and the Dumb's report was published by Lord Egerton in 1889, recommending mandatory education for the deaf.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Before publication, witnesses gave evidence to the commission, including Alexander Graham Bell who promoted the use of the pure oral method of education and proposed to prevent marriage between deaf people; the latter was rejected by the commission.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Also, Edward Gallaudet gave evidence and promoted the developments in Washington, US.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] The Egerton Report supported the oral system.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Owen and Sleight is that the Oral System breaks down in after life, and that its pupils not infrequently resort to writing and the manual alphabet.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] In January 1890, a national conference for the deaf was held in St Saviour's Church for the deaf in London.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Here, Maginn presented his views for improving the deaf education system in Britain.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] He proposed forming a national association for the deaf, and said that the American *Combined Method* education system, which incorporated fingerspelling, Signed English and lip-reading (the manualism approach), which gave access to English as a written language and spoken language, where possible.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] At the conference, it was agreed that there should be a national association representing the deaf community in the British Empire.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Sleight, he permitted the conference to start earlier on morning of 18 January 1890, to hear the proposal for the establishment of a new national association.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] By consent, Francis Maginn was given the floor, and he spoke eloquently for the next half an hour or so about the need of an organised association that would command respect and watch other the interests of the deaf people in Britain, whether these interests be educational, moral or social.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] As a consequence of this ruling, a special committee was set up to establish a constitution made up of six deaf and six hearing men, under the chairmanship of Rev.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Francis would have preferred if no hearing people were involved in this committee but he was over-ruled and acceded to the majority of the conference.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Maginn was one of the 6 Deaf men, who sat on this committee.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] A new constitution was adopted by the committee, but there were concerns over two elements: the name of the new association; and the criteria for membership.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] First, instead of the "National Association for the Deaf," they decided on the name of "British Deaf And Dumb Association." Though it was pointed out that the word "dumb" was no longer in use in America, the term was not removed from their title, BDDA, until 1970.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Secondly, though Maginn wanted only deaf people to become members, the steering group said they would allow hearing members who took an active interest in the welfare of the deaf, provided they were proposed by five deaf people.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Maginn hotly disagreed with this decision, objecting to the idea of the "benevolent paternalism" of the hearing friends of the deaf.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] The Association championed the use of sign language in deaf schools rather than pure oral systems.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] The Association was formed in the Lecture Hall of the Leeds Church Institute, in Albion Place, Leeds, on 24 July 1890.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Persons who can hear taking an active interest in the welfare and education of the deaf and dumb, shall be eligible for admission to ordinary membership on the recommendation of five ordinary members of the association.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Sleight, a hearing man, was elected as the chairman of the association, and Maginn was given the role of regional vice-president; an honorary position with no real power, which was a blow to Maginn's confidence.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Maginn himself gradually withdrew from the Association and concentrated his energy on Ulster Institute for the Deaf.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Maginn confined his later years to work in Belfast until his death in 1918.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] The British Deaf Association didn't have a deaf chair until the appointment of Jock Young as their first Deaf chair in the 1980s and their first deaf chief executive Jeff McWhinney was appointed in the 1990s.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] Despite his failure to create the first fully representative association of deaf people in the UK, he rescinded his role in the BDDA and went back to Belfast to focus on his work as the superintendent at the Ulster Institute for the Deaf, where he was much appreciated by Ulster's deaf community.
[src:british-deaf-association/francis-maginn] He is the only deaf historical figure native to the UK and Ireland that is still talked about and respected by the deaf community a century later.
